Lets play with inheritance, we have a class A and a class B. 
    
    class A{
        private int a;
        A(int a){
            this.a = a;
        }
        public int valA(){
            return this.a;
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A{
        B(int b) {
            super(b);
        }
        public void printA(){
            System.out.println(&quot;The Val of A: &quot;+valA());
        }
        public int valA(){return super.valA()*5;}
    }


What&#39;s special here that we have a method in B that is not defined in class A. Nevertheless, when we create an object of class B and assign it to A, we don&#39;t get any error.

Now we create two objects, of A and B respectively and then assign the object of B to that of A.

        A a = new A(5);
        B b = new B(4);
        a=b;
        System.out.println(a.valA());


When we execute, we get the value as 20. The answer you know is because of Runtime polymorphism that we have overrides valA(). But when we want to execute printA() from a

        a.printA();

The error is a compile time. The reason is simple, the compiler cannot find printA(). And the reason is it was never declared here. But you may ask we defined in B and assigned to A.

The simple answer is compiler ignores it and overrides only the methods and parameters that are declared in B and A.

&gt; **Can we do the opposite?**

Lets try it.

    b = a;

And simply we get the compile time error.

    java: incompatible types: oops.inheritance.A cannot be converted to oops.inheritance.B

And yes the answer is very intuitive because the methods in B have not been A and the compiler knows that this may be a possible case and straight away throws an error that you are doing wrong.

## Now the answer you want.
It is possible to assign an object of subclass to reference of superclass but don&#39;t expect the properties and functions declared in B to be transferred because they are simply dumped.

